  <h2>🛠️ Tools I Actually Use</h2>

  <h3>p5.js</h3>
  <p>
    The gateway drug. Accessible, web-based, huge community.
    <a href="https://p5js.org">Try it in your browser</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Three.js / WebGL</h3>
  <p>
    When you need 3D or serious performance. Steeper learning curve but
    <a href="https://threejs.org">the docs are solid</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>TouchDesigner</h3>
  <p>
    Visual programming for real-time interactive graphics. Expensive but worth it
    if you're doing installations or live visuals.
  </p>

  <h2>🎨 Inspiration</h2>

  <blockquote>
    "Generative art is not about controlling the computer. It's about collaborating with it."
  </blockquote>

  <p>Artists whose work consistently blows my mind:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manfred Mohr</strong> - Algorithmic plotter art from the 70s</li>
    <li><strong>Vera Molnár</strong> - Pioneer of computer art, structural randomness</li>
    <li><strong>Joshua Davis</strong> - Hyperrealistic generative portraits</li>
    <li><strong>Beeple</strong> - Daily renders since 2007 (now selling for millions)</li>
    <li><strongTyler Hobbs</strong> - Algorithmic color field work</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🔧 Code Examples</h2>

  <p>Here's a simple p5.js sketch that creates interesting patterns from circles:</p>

  <pre><code>function setup() {
  createCanvas(600, 600);
  noLoop();
  background(20);
  stroke(255, 50);
}

function draw() {
  for (let i = 0; i < 200; i++) {
    let x = random(width);
    let y = random(height);
    let r = random(10, 100);
    let steps = floor(random(20, 100));

    for (let j = 0; j < steps; j++) {
      let angle = map(j, 0, steps, 0, TWO_PI);
      let px = x + cos(angle) * r * j/steps;
      let py = y + sin(angle) * r * j/steps;
      point(px, py);
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

